06219nam a22007935i 9780824866297DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20172017hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1004868117  a9780824866297  a(DE-B1597)488099  a(OCoLC)990267660  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0230002bisacsh04a282.519090341 aBaker, Don, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatholics and Anti-Catholicism in Chosŏn Korea /cDon Baker, Franklin Rausch; ed. by Christopher J. Bae. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHawai'i Studies on Korea00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tNotes on the Translated Texts and Romanization -- tPart I. The Road to Persecution -- tChapter 1. Korea at the End of the Eighteenth Century -- tChapter 2. Confucian Criticisms of Catholicism -- tChapter 3. The Birth of the Korean Catholic Church -- tChapter 4. A Decade of Hopes and Fears -- tChapter 5. Nationalism and Evaluations of Hwang Sayŏng and His Silk Letter -- tPart II. In Their Own Words -- tChapter 6. A Conversation on Catholicism by Sunam Ahn Chŏngbok -- tChapter 7. The Silk Letter of Hwang Sayŏng -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKorea’s first significant encounter with the West occurred in the last quarter of the eighteenth century when a Korean Catholic community emerged on the peninsula. Decades of persecution followed, resulting in the deaths of thousands of Korean Catholics. Don Baker provides an invaluable analysis of late-Chosŏn (1392–1897) thought, politics, and society to help readers understand the response of Confucians to Catholicism and of Korean Catholics to years of violent harassment. His analysis is informed by two remarkable documents expertly translated with the assistance of Franklin Rausch and annotated here for the first time: an anti-Catholic essay written in the 1780s by Confucian scholar Ahn Chŏngbok (1712–1791) and a firsthand account of the 1801 anti-Catholic persecution by one of its last victims, the religious leader Hwang Sayŏng (1775–1801).Confucian assumptions about Catholicism are revealed in Ahn’s essay, Conversation on Catholicism. The work is based on the scholar’s exchanges with his son-in-law, who joined the small group of Catholics in the 1780s. Ahn argues that Catholicism is immoral because it puts more importance on the salvation of one’s soul than on what is best for one’s family or community. Conspicuously absent from his Conversation is the reason behind the conversions of his son-in-law and a few other young Confucian intellectuals. Baker examines numerous Confucian texts of the time to argue that, in the late eighteenth century, Korean Confucians were tormented by a growing concern over human moral frailty. Some among them came to view Catholicism as a way to overcome their moral weakness, become virtuous, and, in the process, gain eternal life. These anxieties are echoed in Hwang’s Silk Letter, in which he details for the bishop in Beijing his persecution and the decade preceding it. He explains why Koreans joined (and some abandoned) the Catholic faith and their devotion to the new religion in the face of torture and execution. Together the two texts reveal much about not only Korean beliefs and values of two centuries ago, but also how Koreans viewed their country and their king as well as China and its culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAnti-CatholicismzKoreaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh1 aBae, Christopher J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRausch, Franklin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106389360 cprintz978082486626640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824866297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824866297/original  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-063893-6  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-071954-3  DG Plus eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DEGb2017  aZDB-23-DGGb2017